<HEAD>Commander Warns Officers Against `Rabble' Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior commander ordered his officers Sunday to view film footage of troops brutally beating Arab prisoners and said the Israeli army must not become `` a rabble army.'' Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Amram </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitzna </PERSON>, head of the Central Command that is in charge of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> of the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, gathered all officers over the rank of platoon commander Sunday and showed them the footage shot by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio reported. `` I'm against those who think we can sweep internal problems under the carpet just because they're not pretty,'' <PERSON> Mitzna </PERSON> said earlier on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. `` We have to make sure we do n't become a rabble army.'' The film, which showed four soldiers in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> kicking and beating two Palestinians last Thursday, shocked many Israelis who believed violence by soldiers during three months of Palestinian demonstrations had receded after new army orders last week limited the use of force. Some members of Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bloc </ORGANIZATION> defended the soldiers. `` I'm against the lynch atmosphere,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> legislator <PERSON> Pinchas </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>. `` There was no need to arrest the soldiers.'' Transport Minister <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Korfu </PERSON>, also of <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, told the Cabinet Sunday the press should be barred from the occupied lands for three months. `` We are in a confrontation,'' <PERSON> Korfu </PERSON> later told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` We must take these minimal measures when we know for certain -LRB- the media -RRB- is responsible for some of the violence.'' According to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures, 74 Arabs have been killed by the Israelis during the violent in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> since Dec. 10. Hundreds have been wounded and there have been many cases of soldiers severely beating Palestinians. The CBS film showed four soldiers, members of a tank unit, kicking the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> whose hands were tied behind their backs and smashing them on the legs and arms with fist-sized rocks. The four were arrested and their deputy unit commander, a captain, was suspended. It was announced Saturday that the four soldiers would be tried by a military court. <PERSON> Mitzna </PERSON> ordered the release of the two Arabs. <PERSON> Amalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Harpaz </PERSON>, the mother of one of the four soldiers filmed by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, said her son <PERSON> Saguy </PERSON> had changed since he began serving in the occupied territories 10 weeks ago. `` I educated my son to go the army, take responsibility and defend the country,'' she told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` What has happened is that he has turned into a beater of women and children.'' She is a resident of <ORGANIZATION> Kibbutz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gesher </ORGANIZATION>, a communal settlement. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said several lawyers have offered to represent the soldiers without charge. It reported the lawyers said if anyone was responsible for a crime, it is <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s leaders.
</TEXT>
