<HEAD>Sunken Barge Raised, Minor Oil Spill Detected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with oil pumping under way,
increased estimate on surface oil spill, updated figure on amount
of this spill cleaned up. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Western
Washington ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG ESSER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANACORTES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A salvage crew raised a sunken oil barge Sunday from the murky depths of <LOCATION> Guemes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Channel </LOCATION>, one month after it sank and spilled some 70,000 gallons of heavy bunker oil into <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s inland waters. With the inverted barge held at the surface by thick cables strung from two giant cranes, crews began pumping the more than 300,000 gallons of oil that remained in the vessel into a second barge. Officials said they wanted to get the stricken barge floating on its own before they attempted to slowly roll it right side up. A helicopter hovered overhead to track the movement of an oil sheen that appeared as the barge was raised. The sheen was caused by 500 to 1,000 gallons of lighter oil that was detected after the barge broke the surface about 7 a.m., said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> of the state Division of Emergency Management. The barge initially held about 22,000 gallons of light oil in addition to the heavy oil. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said surface skimmer boats had cleaned up about 160 gallons, while absorbent pads collected an additional, undetermined amount. The oil sheen moved about two miles south. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Eldo </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLong </PERSON> said the sheen reached some kelp beds near <LOCATION> Burrows </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, but did not touch any beaches. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecology </ORGANIZATION> workers said three seabirds were contaminated, but they did not appear badly injured and were not captured for cleaning. Marine biologists and state environmental experts were assessing the damage from the bunker oil spill, which had been difficult to determine because the heavier-than-water oil had sunk. But <PERSON> Ats </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiuchi </PERSON>, a DOE spokesman, said it appeared the fragile, inner coastal environment had avoided a disaster that, if the barge had spilled its entire cargo, would have been the worst oil spill in the state's history. <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Shannon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> has found some oil in sea cucumbers, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>, the lab's director of operations The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> tug `` Spike'' used absorbent pads to clean up some oil after the barge was raised while a second boat was positioned near <LOCATION> Shannon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, 100 yards away, to prevent any oil from reaching shore. The 176-foot-long barge, operated by Olympic Tug and Barge of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, sank Jan. 31 in about 130 feet of water four miles west of <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION> and about 100 yards off <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Point </PERSON>. The barge had been loaded at an oil refinery at <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION> and was being towed by a tug to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> when it began listing and capsized. The cause of the sinking remained undetermined. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Eldo </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLong </PERSON> said the barge will be taken to the <LOCATION> Anacortes </LOCATION> city dock where a boom would be put around it and any remaining holes would be patched. Eventually it will be taken to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, he said.
</TEXT>
