<HEAD>Newspaper: United States Has Sent Envoy To Iran For Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> newspaper said Sunday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has sent a secret envoy to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to discuss re-establishing diplomatic links. The Observer, in an unattributed story, did not identify the official but said he is apparently a close friend of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and went to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> two weeks ago. It said the envoy was traveling under the name of <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. The Observer said the envoy met middle-ranking Iranian officials, who asked for assurances that any arms embargo against them as proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should be delayed until early this summer. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeking a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ban on arms sales because <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has not accepted a cease-fire agreement in its eight-year war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. There have been no diplomatic relations since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> was stormed Nov. 4, 1979, and held for 444 days with diplomats and others kept hostage inside.
