<FIRST>r a PM-SuperPooch     02-28 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Super Pooch,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nosey Narcotics Pooch Puts Pinch On Sneaky Smugglers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaping luggage and sniffing out sneaky smugglers, the latest addition to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>'s K-9 corps has racked up impressive credits in his first two months on the beat, his human colleagues say. King, a romping 2-year-old cross between a black Labrador retriever and a German short-haired pointer, has a nose that makes news. Since the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> gave King to <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> police, he has sniffed out $ 86,000 in drug-scented cash, 347 pounds of cocaine and helped collar four suspects, said police Lt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. The beloved rookie, one of three canines used by <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> police at the airport, has all but matched the 400-pound career total of <PERSON> Ringo </PERSON>, who just retired after about a decade, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. `` He's an up-and-coming dog,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said of the enthusiastic pooch, who with handler Detective <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON>, graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> dog training school in Front Royal, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. King and <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> were still getting used to the domestic flight areas of <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> after their December graduation when they made their first score Dec. 17 A man carrying Christmas presents on a flight from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> fit the profile of a smuggler. <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> police had been suspicious. The man agreed to a search and King `` alerted'' to a drug odor in his packages. More than $ 40,000 in drug-tainted cash was discovered, <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> said. The fact that a specially trained dog identified the money as having been associated with narcotics was probable cause to seize it, <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> said. Soon afterward, King found a similar amount of drug-tainted cash packed in a <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benz </ORGANIZATION>. The two occupants of the car were arrested and are awaiting trial in <ORGANIZATION> Dade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> said. King's abilities also led to the discovery of 185 pounds of cocaine and the arrest of two <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> employees on Feb. 1. The next day, he sniffed out 155 pounds of cocaine concealed underneath the floor in the belly of an L-1011 aircraft. He detected 7 pounds of cocaine on an earlier search to bring his total to 347 pounds, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. `` I worked mostly narcotics for the last 16 years,'' said <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON>. `` The biggest seizure I made was 600 pounds and it took me almost 10 years. But working with a detector dog, we've found almost 400 pounds in the first two months we were back from school. `` We're both still a green team. I've been a police officer for 18 years but I feel like a rookie again. It's like a whole new career,'' he said. While King has a `` super-fine nose,'' he is not perfect, <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> said. King gets tired sometimes while working his eight-hour shift, `` but so far he's been on the money,'' he said. Detector dogs can not sniff the enormous volume of luggage, freight and planes used to smuggle narcotics and money through this primary port of entry for drugs, <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> said. Any dog and its handler are only as good as the watchful authorities who suggest likely targets. `` It was mostly luck and being in the right place at the right time,'' <PERSON> Buzzi </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
