<FIRST>r i PM-MilitaryCourts     02-28 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Courts,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel's Military Court System Under Hail Of Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOD, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON>, accused of hurling a firebomb at <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers, saw his lawyer for the first time five minutes before he appeared in military court. The 19-year-old signed a confession written in <LOCATION> Hebrew </LOCATION>, a language he does not know, and said interrogators abused him. As authorities round up growing numbers of Arab suspects in an effort to quell nearly three months of unrest, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s methods of detaining and trying Palestinians has drawn a hail of criticism. `` I feel totally helpless in this sham of a system,'' said <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON>, a Palestinian who graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> law school in <LOCATION> Charlottesville </LOCATION>. `` In 98 percent of the cases, lawyers can not see Palestinian clients until after they ` confess,' and judges will accept the ` confession' at face value, no matter what you say,'' <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON>, shackled and dressed in a blue-jeans jacket, flashed a V-for-victory sign as he entered the tiny courtroom in a closed army base. He waved to his father, whom he was seeing for the first time since his arrest. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON> had been held incommunicado for 18 days, until he signed a four-page confession. He said he signed only after interrogators beat him, deprived him of sleep and forced him to squat in a corner for hours. <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said it was unlikely his client's contentions would be accepted in court. Allegations of unfairness in the military court system prompted the attorneys' association in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> to decide to boycott all military court proceedings. But Israeli officials argue the system is fair. `` There are some exceptions. But a defendant who feels he was mistreated during interrogation can raise the issue in court, where due process of law is ensured,'' army prosecutor <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> <PERSON> Giora </PERSON>, a native of <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, said in an interview. <PERSON> Giora </PERSON> and other Israelis argue the only obvious shortcoming in the military court system was redressed by Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> earlier this month when he announced that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, after 20 years of occupation, would establish army appeal courts. <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said figures assembled by Palestinian lawyers show the total number of Arab detainees, normally about 3,000 at any one time, has doubled and the army has set up four new prisons with tent barracks in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. According to the army, 1,927 Palestinians were arrested and 93 placed in jail for six months without trial under emergency regulations from Dec. 8 to Feb. 9. The Arab-owned <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> puts the number of Arabs jailed without trial at 147. The process from arrest to trial in the military court system is well documented. A Palestinian suspected of participating in anti-Israeli activities is usually detained in the middle of the night because soldiers fear their presence in Arab towns or refugee camps during the day might spark protests. The detainee is handcuffed, often blindfolded, and taken to a military prison. No arrest warrant is ever shown and family members are not told where the suspect is being taken. It often takes a lawyer several weeks to track down his new client, who can be held incommunicado for up to six months. A judge is required to order a detention extension after the first 18 days. `` During the period of interrogation, the detainee is routinely subjected to beatings, forced to spend long hours in uncomfortable positions, threatened and submitted to other psychological measures,'' <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said. `` Usually before the first 18-day period is up, the defendant breaks down and confesses to a variety of illegal activities,'' <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said. `` Only after this is he permitted to see an attorney, and only then is the attorney told what charges his client faces.'' <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON> entered court with five other Arab defendants, four of whom had no attorney present. <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> was able to see his client and the charge sheet against him only minutes before the court session began. <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> argued in court that <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON> signed the confession only after being abused. He asked for, and was granted, a separate hearing about the admissiblity of the evidence. <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said he did not intend actually to present a case on whether the evidence should be admitted, but only to use the extra time to try to plea bargain a shorter sentence. `` If I protest, his interrogator will deny it and he will just end up getting a tougher sentence,'' <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said. `` What hurts most about the process is the pretense of propriety,'' he said. `` With a judge and a prosecutor and a defense attorney, it looks all right from the outside. But in fact, on a certain level, I feel I am a collaborator in the evil system.'' `` At least I brought him some cigarettes,'' <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Leban </PERSON>, shaking his head as he left court. `` I've turned into a social worker more than a lawyer in this system.''
</TEXT>
