<FIRST>r a PM-TribalClaim     02-28 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tribal Claim,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribes See Chance To Settle Longstanding Dispute Over Water
Project</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW TOWN, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fertile <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> bottom lands where the <LOCATION> Arikara </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hidatsa </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Mandan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> thrived for seven centuries are gone forever, buried beneath the waters of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sakakawea </LOCATION>. The 200-mile-long reservoir drove the Indians onto higher, less productive land, sliced their reservation into isolated sections and is blamed for precipitating soaring unemployment and alcoholism. The three tribes, who say they were coerced into surrendering the bottom lands without just compensation as the lake filled behind <LOCATION> Garrison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dam </LOCATION>, believe they have a chance this year to get $ 178.4 million that they and a special federal commission think they deserve. `` The problem has been with us for 40 years. The time is right for a resolution,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> Lone Fight. The tribes, which total about 7,700 people, are asking the state's congressional delegation to introduce legislation that would give them $ 3.6 million a year for 50 years plus 4 percent interest on the unpaid balance of the settlement. The money would come from federal hydropower revenues, rather than the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, which tribal leaders believe should make the legislation more palatable to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The bill also would fund municipal water projects on the reservation and authorize, but not pay for, replacement of a hospital and other facilities destroyed by the reservoir. Lone Fight says the bill `` is something that's supportable'' in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> opposes further compensation for the tribes. Rural electric cooperatives do n't like the idea of dipping into hydropower revenues. And members of the state's congressional delegation have yet to support the bill. `` We hope that something can be introduced this session. But until we can find something that everyone feels comfortable with, nothing can be introduced,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrem </PERSON>, an aide to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Indian Affairs. The tribes accepted $ 12.6 million from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1950, but <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Dam </PERSON> was already built and <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakakawea </PERSON> was forming when the money was offered. The tribes and their supporters say the Indians had no choice but to take the settlement. `` When the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> people were negotiating for the best possible deal, the water was up to their ankles ... and the offers were going down,'' Lone Fight said. When dam construction began in the 1940s, 90 percent of the Indians lived and farmed in the river valley, as their ancestors had for seven centuries. Unemployment on the reservation was negligible. Today, unemployment exceeds 50 percent and alcoholism is rampant, problems that have been linked to the disruption caused by Garrison Dam. About 3,400 Indians live on the reservation; another 4,300 tribal members live elsewhere. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakakawea </PERSON> is named for a Shoshone guide who worked for the <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> expedition up the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in 1804. `` In my 66 years, I have seen a drastic change from being self-sufficent to being a very desperate economic situation,'' said <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Grinnell </PERSON>, a tribal judge. <ORGANIZATION> Grinnell </ORGANIZATION> grew up on a family farm near <LOCATION> Elbowoods </LOCATION>, the reservation's main town before it was inundated. The tribes grew their own vegetables and cattle, cut firewood from trees along the river and mined nearby coal deposits, <ORGANIZATION> Grinnell </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We never heard of unemployment because everyone had their farms, and those who had jobs did n't farm,'' <ORGANIZATION> Grinnell </ORGANIZATION> said. A five-member panel appointed by <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> concluded in 1986 that the tribes were owed $ 178 million to $ 412 million in compensation. The <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> agreed with Indian claims that the lake destroyed their self-sufficient way of life and precipitated the tribes' continuing social problems. If the tribes get the settlement, the money would be earmarked for programs, such as work projects and alcohol treatment, that would attack the reservation's social ills, Lone Fight said. However, in a recent meeting with tribal leaders, Assistant Secretary for <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swimmer </ORGANIZATION> claimed that the tribes have been adequately compensated through the federal services they receive. Swimmer's position was characterized by <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, an attorney for the tribes, as `` disingenuous.'' Bureau of Indian Affairs officials will meet soon with members of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s congressional delegation to discuss the tribes' proposal, <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said
</TEXT>
