<FIRST>r a PM-FiskUniversity     02-28 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fisk University,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enrollment, Endowment Improve At Black University</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICKI BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Enrollment is up and the debt is down at <ORGANIZATION> Fisk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where only a few years ago students shivered in unheated dormitories because the historically black private institution could not pay its gas bill. As Fisk winds down its celebration of Black History Month, which included the dedication of a stamp honoring author <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, faculty and students also celebrated the university's return from the brink of financial disaster When the <ORGANIZATION> Nashville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> cut off service in early 1984 until <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> paid a $ 170,000 debt, students brought space heaters to class and joined with faculty and staff members to raise funds to ensure the university's survival. The overall debt mounted to $ 4.1 million, but classes continued. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponder </PERSON>, appointed <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>'s president in July 1984, led the school on a course of austerity programs and aggressive fund-raising. When Ponder was told, for example, that boiler repairs would cost $ 350,000, he found a Fisk alumnus, a maintenance expert, who did it for only $ 60,000. Ponder acknowledged in a recent interview that things are better at <LOCATION> Fisk </LOCATION>, but added `` you have to get the public to understand that help is still needed to get the resources to move this institution ... to the forefront of educational institutions in this country. `` I do n't say that lightly. That's where we've been and we will get back,'' said Ponder, who said the school did not lower its academic standards during its financial troubles. Today, debt at <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> has been reduced to $ 200,000 and its endowment has reached $ 3.9 million. An unrestricted gift of $ 1.3 million by entertainer <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> in December 1986 gave the school a boost, but officials say they have received substantial grass-roots support, too. However, three of the university's 23 trustees announced Friday that they will resign at the end of the school year. One trustee said the resignations were related to the accountability of those charged with day-to-day administration. <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>'s financial aid director and assistant director were fired in December for allegedly failing to fill out forms to receive financial aid. Faculty salaries have increased 30 percent over the last three years to an average of $ 32,000 for a tenured professor, although still below the $ 35,000 to $ 40,000 Ponder said is appropriate. Aggressive recruiting of students brought enrollment, which dipped to 500 at one point, up to 644 students in the 1988 spring semester, an increase of 27 percent over the 1987 spring semester, said <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> DeShields </PERSON>, director of the office of admissions and records. <PERSON> Bryon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>, a student from <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>'s role in black history in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was important to him. `` <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> introduced the black spiritual to the world, it was active in the civil rights movement, W.E.B. <PERSON> DuBois </PERSON> went to college here,'' <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON> said. In addition, he said, `` My understanding is that a degree from <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> is as respected as one from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>.'' The financial crisis at the school had some positive benefits for the Fisk community, said <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, now a graduate student. `` The student body handled the crisis well, we shared space heaters. It united us. We were able to confront a problem and come through it,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> sid. The university, founded in 1867 by the Freedmen's <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> during Reconstruction, is no stranger to struggle. In fact, the campus was purchased with $ 150,000 raised by the college's Jubilee Singers during a European tour in the 1870s. The earnings of the singers, whose tours still bring $ 60,000 a year to <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>, also paid for building Jubilee Hall, whose exterior was recently restored with a $ 150,000 federal grant. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a poet who was a diplomat and an early organizer of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People, was a professor at <LOCATION> Fisk </LOCATION> in the early 1930s. W.E.B. <PERSON> DuBois </PERSON>, a philosopher and writer who graduated from <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> in 1888, also helped found the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> and was the first black to earn a doctorate from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think students are attracted here because it has the reputation of a good community. When they get here, they find out we have a dynamic science faculty and many of our students go to medical and dental schools,'' Ponder said. About 60 percent of <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> graduates enroll for postgraduate study. <PERSON> Revais </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, executive assistant to the president and a history professor, said <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>'s financial problems mirrored those of other liberal arts college, but were worse. `` In the 1960s and 1970s the philosophy of supporting a liberal arts education dried up and the interest shifted to business degrees,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said the quality of education at <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> has never suffered and that peeling paint and cold classrooms do n't mean poor academics. `` I try to tell my students that there has always been an element of suffering in the tradition of black education,'' he said.
