<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Mexican nationals, including a former Mexican police detective charged in the torture-murder of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug agent, were convicted of conspiring to murder a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs agent. The charges grew out of a series of meetings with an undercover investigator in which defendant <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> offered to murder the Customs agent for a $ 25,000 fee. No killing took place. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, 29, who also faces charges in the 1985 slaying of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON>, was convicted Friday of conspiracy to murder a federal agent and conspiracy to kidnap a federal agent. Two men <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> hired in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to assist him, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldonado </PERSON>, 25, and <PERSON> Fabian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, 22, also were convicted in the conspiracy. <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> was acquitted on a charge that he traveled to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to carry out the murder plot. The men could receive life imprisonment. Sentencing was scheduled for April 18 before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rymer </PERSON>. Lawyers for the defendants had argued that <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> and the two men he hired never intended to carry out the murder, but had planned all along to stage a `` rip-off'' of the undercover drug agent with whom they were negotiating. They believed that the undercover agent was a narcotics dealer. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, a former homicide investigator for the Mexican state judicial police, tol