<FIRST>r w AM-DietStudy     02-28 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diet Study,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fragmentary Diet Studies Confuse Food-For-Health Views, Says
Expert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fad health diets and `` marketplace gimmickry'' are giving Americans a distorted view of the type and amount of foods needed to help prevent chronic disease, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor. In a paper prepared for congressional testimony on Tuesday, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said isolated studies, taken out of context and promoted by special economic interests, often trigger changes in the American diet that may actually be harmful. `` Too many Americans believe in magic bullets. Too many corporations believe in profit-rich products with very specific health claims,'' said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>. Such `` marketplace gimmickry,'' he said, does not help Americans avoid the so-called `` diseases of affluence'' of osteoporosis and heart attack. In a paper prepared for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> governmental affairs committee, <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> recommended that the government establish a national research center to collect and analyze nutrition information so Americans can receive more accurate information on diet and health. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> directed a massive study of the diet and lifestyle of 6,500 persons in 130 locations in the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in an effort to determine how nutrition affects such diseases as cancer and heart attack. He said the study is not yet finished, but results so far cast doubt on some of the popular American beliefs about nutrition and health. Among his observations: _ American studies have shown that a serum cholesterol reading of 180 milligrams per decaliter can reduce the risk of heart attack Yet, another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> study showed that a reduction in cholesterol raises the risk of colon cancer. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said that in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the cholesterol levels are far below the typical American level, and the incidence of colon cancer also is low. This shows, he said, that the study showing an increase in colon cancer with lower cholesterol `` is an experimental aberration.'' _ Excess calories may not be the sole cause of obesity, <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> said He said the Chinese consume about 20 percent more calories than do Americans, yet obesity is rare among the Chinese. He said Chinese average only about 15 percent of their calories in the form of fat _ far below the typical American. _ Some American studies have suggested that an increase in fiber in the diet may lead to a loss of minerals <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> said the Chinese consume about 34 grams of fiber per day, versus about 10 grams for most Americans, and yet the Chinese show healthy levels of iron, zinc and magnesium, all important minerals.
