<FIRST>r i AM-China-LaborMarket     02-28 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Labor Market,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing City Opens Labor Market for Those Seeking New Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 1,000 people, trying to buck the Chinese system of assigned jobs for life, gathered Sunday at the opening of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s first citywide labor market. A mostly young crowd, bundled up in heavy greatcoats, peered at job description posters lining the street and discussed work opportunities with representatives of 22 factories and companies who manned desks inside the `` Labor Exchange Center.'' The center, said deputy chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenyong </PERSON>, was set up by the city <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> to carry out the government policy of allowing people to find jobs more suitable to their needs and skills. Those who pay a fee of 27 cents will have their names placed on the center's computerized list and receive help in finding a new job, he said. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanxin </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Tienma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which supplies tourist items to department stores, said many people want to find new work closer to their homes. `` Others just do n't like their present jobs,'' he said, adding that his company found seven prospective new employees Sunday morning. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Hongjun </PERSON>, 34, said she was applying for a job with a <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> wine company because it has night shifts, allowing her to care for a sick sister during the day. She said she could also take a bus to the winery, rather than commute by bicycle as she does to her current job. A personnel officer at <ORGANIZATION> Qinghua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which is looking for nine cooks, electricians, drivers and other workers, said factory workers are attracted to the school's long summer and winter holidays. Many, said <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingxiang </PERSON>, also want their children to attend the excellent kindergarten and primary schools run by the university. Since the 1949 communist takeover, Chinese have had little choice in determining their career. Under a system known as `` fen pei,'' Chinese were assigned a job for life from which they could not be fired, but neither could they leave. High school and elementary school graduates were assigned work in local businesses or, if they come from the countryside, were generally returned to the land to farm with the rest of their family. College graduates, a scarce resource here, were sent anywhere in the country that needed them. A student, majoring in English literature at prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, could, for example, wind up in barren <LOCATION> Qinghai </LOCATION> province, teaching English to barely literate peasants. But in recent years, cracks have appeared in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s `` iron rice bowl'' as the country has sought to speed its economic development. The Chinese government has recognized that its traditional labor system has deadened worker creativity and kept workers from fully using their talents. It also has split families, especially those of the educated classes. Indeed, it is not unusual for couples with college educations to be assigned jobs in different provinces, thousands of miles away from one another. As a result, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has begun loosening restrictions on job-hopping and encouraging the 20 million people who have gone off on their own to set up small private businesses. However, the work units to which each Chinese is assigned still regard employees as the property of the unit and often refuse a job transfer or exact compensation for the loss of a worker. Engineers, scientists and other trained people in particular have had difficulty leaving their old jobs because of their value to the work unit. That creates the ironic condition that the better one does one's job here, the less of a chance one has to leave it for something better `` It's true that if a person has a position of responsibility it will be more difficult for him to change jobs,'' said the center's <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> `` But if his work unit refuses to let him go, we will do what we can to help, including assist in finding a replacement.'' Similar labor markets have appeared at the city district level in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, but the center that opened Sunday is the first to cover the entire city. Illegal work markets have also sprung up in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and in several other <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> cities. Their purpose generally is not to help employed people find a new job, but to help unemployed peasants enter the urban labor force, allowing them to abandon the difficult life in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s countryside. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> said the city-wide labor market will also stay open in the evenings and on Sundays to accommodate people who have difficulty getting away from their jobs to look for new ones.
</TEXT>
