<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Romans     02-28 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Romans,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roman Amphitheater Found In London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archaeologists said Sunday they discovered the remains of a Roman amphitheater 15 feet below <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s financial district in one of the most important finds in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> this century. Historians had been looking for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s amphitheater for 300 years. Amphitheaters were used for weapons training and military parades, as well as fights with animals and gladiatorial combat. Archaeologists from the Museum of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> uncovered the eastern end of the amphitheater's stone walls during excavations going on since last July, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>, the museum's excavations officer, in an interview with The Observer weekly. The Corporation of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, which administers <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, gave the museum $ 176,000 to dig on the site next to the medieval Guildhall, where the corporation meets. An art gallery and an office building has been planned for the amphitheater's site. The Observer reported that the corporation will talk with the archaeologists and architects this week to discuss preservation of the uncovered amphitheater remains. A clash could develop if the corporation wants to rebury the site and proceed with the art gallery and offices, The Observer said. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> was founded by the <ORGANIZATION> Romans </ORGANIZATION>, who called it Londinium. The Romans stayed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> from A.D. 43 to 410. The excavators think the amphitheater was built between A.D. 70 and 140, during the heyday of Roman <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Corroded coins found on the site may help to date the ruin more exactly. The center of the amphitheater is under the open courtyard in front of Guildhall. Almost all the area where the seats and walls would have been is under Guildhall itself, the art gallery site and neighboring buildings. The excavators say the amphitheater was oval shaped, 100 yards from east to west and 80 yards north to south. That is small compared with Roman amphitheaters found in southern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, but about the same size as four others in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> _ at <LOCATION> Cirencester </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chester </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chichester </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Silchester </PERSON>.
