<HEAD>Justice Changes Account Of Meese's Role In Israeli Spy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For nine months, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has given the impression Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> removed himself from the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> spy case. But now it acknowledges he was briefed twice about the case and it says he never was excluded. In what chief department spokesman <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> called a correction, he said <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is only excluded from the espionage case against the <ORGANIZATION> Israeli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officer who recruited <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> counterterrorism analyst <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> as a spy. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is free to be briefed and even to make decisions in the still-open <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> case to the extent that they do n't involve the case against Israeli Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Aviem </PERSON> <PERSON> Sella </PERSON>, <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s own lawyer, <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>, was unaware of that distinction as recently as last week even though it was <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>'s work for <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sella </PERSON> in separate cases that triggered the exclusion, known as a recusal The turnabout comes as a government source said independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> is examining another <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> recusal for clues about his motives in dealing with a <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> oil pipeline proposal in 1985. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> hired <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> last May to represent him in <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s investigation of whether the attorney general and his attorney, <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, violated or conspired to violate a federal law barring bribes to foreign officials In May 1985, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was recused from all matters involving <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, but arranged for <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> to meet National Security Adviser <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON> to promote the pipeline. Investigators say that examining that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> recusal might help determine whether the attorney general was aiding <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s plan or, as <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> argues, directing it to the proper official. At the Office of Government Ethics last week, General Counsel <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> explained: `` If you're a federal official and you've hired a law firm to represent you, you should recuse yourself, that is, take no action in any matter involving that firm _ just as a matter of appearances even if you have no financial stake.'' For that reason, <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> advised <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> officials last May: `` I hereby recuse myself from participating in any matter before the department in which the law firm -LRB- of <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Cassidy </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Larroca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> -RRB- represents any party or is otherwise involved.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported then that the recusal covered the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> affair. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> did not dispute that. <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> was sentenced last year to life in prison for giving reams of secrets to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> agents. But Justice officials still pursued the case, in part, because <PERSON> Sella </PERSON> had fled to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and has not been brought to trial here. So there was surprise and consternation when the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported Feb. 19: `` After being briefed on the case last month, ... <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> ordered that the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> case be kept officially open so investigators can pursue their inquiry.'' Asked by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> last Monday for an explanation, <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said, `` I have problems with that account because <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> is recused in <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> bucked the question to deputy chief spokesman <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Korten </PERSON>. Citing the same problem, <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> bucked it to <LOCATION> Eastland </LOCATION>, who was with <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> until Wednesday. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> said he'd never discussed <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> with <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> because `` I think he certainly has recused himself because I am representing <PERSON> Sella </PERSON>.'' Expressing surprise at the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> account, <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> said, `` At the department, they have known all along that it has been very much up front that he is not involved in <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON>.'' While <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> sought an answer, a senior department official, demanding anonymity, said Wednesday there was no problem because <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was merely briefed and made no decisions. Some former department lawyers dispute that view. One, who once worked in the attorney general's office, said, `` A recusal has always meant a Chinese wall. You are not even kept up to date.'' A former <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> career lawyer said that, to avoid making a decision by `` a wink or a nod,'' briefings were restricted to situations where the information was essential to decisions in other areas. But Friday afternoon, <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> provided an official explanation that did not claim an exception for briefings. He said the client lists regularly provided by <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>'s firm `` have not included the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> case, and so the attorney general is not recused from <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON>.'' `` The lists do include the <PERSON> Sella </PERSON> case, and the attorney general has been very careful to avoid taking any action in that case or in any other related case where his action might at all affect the <PERSON> Sella </PERSON> case.'' <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> denied <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> kept the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> case open. `` He did n't have to, because it has been open for some time. <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> acknowledged that last month and on one previously undisclosed occasion Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON>, head of the criminal division, had briefed <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> about the <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON> case `` without touching on <PERSON> Sella </PERSON>.'' Why the turnabout? `` We were confused about the <PERSON> Sella </PERSON> case,'' <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON> said. `` It was an honest error.''
