RSON> Mahan </PERSON>. `` Where <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made his mistake was in not responding back to him. He just let it sit there.'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s main television weapon in the Feb. 8 <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses was his controversial `` <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>'' ad _ 30 seconds of soothing music taking the edge off a sharp message. `` Because of trade barriers, a $ 10,000 Chrysler K-car costs $ 48,000 in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> says as scenes from an auto assembly plant fill the screen. The clean-cut candidate appears onscreen in white shirt, tie and black overcoat to conclude his message. If the Koreans wo n't change their ways, he says, they'll be `` left asking themselves how many Americans are going to pay $ 48,000 for one of their Hyundais.'' Trade experts say the ad is erroneous. They also complain that it oversimplifies a very complicated issue, but that is precisely why it works. `` It's more in the realm of people's thinking,'' said <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Roeder </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was a good example for <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> to use and it obviously worked here. As far as what the actual cost might be, in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> that's irrelevant because the caucuses are over.'' One reason the <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> ad and a hay-filled farming ad appeared to reap such dramatic results for <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> was that they built on the type of grass-roots organization impossible to recreate across the vast Super Tuesday landscape. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, for example, had worked <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> exhaustively for more than a year, spending hundreds of days there, meeting thousands of activists, shaking countless hands, spending innumerable hours on the telephone. He was no stranger by the time his ads went on television after Christmas. `` His TV spots would not have had an impact had it not been for his foundation out here,'' said <PERSON> Roeder </PERSON>. `` It's only at the end that TV mattered and had any sort of impact at all.''
