<FIRST>r a AM-Mecham-Primer Bjt   02-28 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mecham-Primer, Bjt,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeachment Process Traces Back To English System Of Removing
Cruel Kings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> opens Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s impeachment trial Monday, it will embark on a course laid out in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> as a way to remove cruel kings and brought to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in Colonial days as a way to protect democracy. But despite the long and sometimes colorful history of impeachment, legal scholars say the seldom-used laws are ill defined. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> lawmakers grappling with <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s fate have to make up many rules as they go along. `` The Arizona Constitution provides few standards or procedures for how the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is to perform its role,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> law professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Glennon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was impeached Feb. 5 by the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> on allegations of concealing a $ 350,000 campaign loan, misusing $ 80,000 from a special fund and attempting to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a state official. The impeachment amounts to an indictment, and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> process to a trial. The 30 senators will act as both judge and jury for the embattled <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> governor. But an impeachment trial is not a criminal trial _ it's purely part of the political system. The only penalty the governor faces is removal from office. `` It's basically _ ` You're fired,''' <PERSON> Glennon </PERSON> said. `` Impeachment is a way to get out of office those officials that violate the public trust.'' Even before <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s impeachment trial begins, political arguments arising from the legal vagueness have abounded in the Republican-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. While setting the rules, the senators have agreed, for example, that the evidence against <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> must be `` clear and convincing'' in order to find him guilty. That's not as rigid as the requirement in criminal trials that guilt be `` beyond a reasonable doubt,'' but it is tougher than the civil standard of a `` preponderance of the evidence'' _ more than half _ for a verdict. `` There is nothing in the constitution about that and the senators can do whatever they want,'' <PERSON> Glennon </PERSON> said. `` It's typical of the constitution to leave things so open. ` Due process' and ` equal protection' are very vague words but we have thousands and thousands of cases that define what they mean. In impeachment, we have so few cases, it's not always clear,'' he said. Senators are constitutionally required `` to do justice according to law and evidence.'' Even the definition of an impeachable offense has been argued through history. Former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, whose Watergate activities were probed by an impeachment committee in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, argued that a misdeed had to be dastardly enough to deserve a criminal indictment to be impeachable. But that's not necessarily true, <PERSON> Glennon </PERSON> said. Impeachment does n't have to involve illegal activities _ only `` high crimes, misdemeanors, or malfeasance'' in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. No court in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> has specifically defined high crimes and misdemeanors regarding impeachment, but the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has said malfeasance occurs if an elected official commits `` an act which is either positively wrong or unlawful,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Chief Justice <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>. The trial may look to observers like a criminal trial, but all 30 senators will have a chance to question witnesses, much like a congressional hearing. A two-thirds vote _ 20 senators _ is required to convict the governor. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, the chief justice, will sit as a referee and be called the `` presiding officer.'' Five members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, through their attorneys, will sit as the `` Board of Managers'' and handle the prosecution. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> will have his own defense attorneys. And there wo n't be any attempt to have an impartial jury. `` It is quite clear that the framers of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution -LRB- from which the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> law is drawn -RRB- chose to make the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as judge and jury,'' <PERSON> Glennon </PERSON> said. `` The governor has no right to 12 ignorant lay people in this deal. In impeachment, there is no intent to have an impartial jury. The framers thought the fact that the senators would know something about the case was good.'' <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> also has been indicted in state district court on six felony counts involving the $ 350,000 loan, which amounted to about a third of his campaign war chest, and faces a criminal trial March 22. He faces a recall election May 17. He is the 16th governor to be impeached in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history; six have been convicted and removed from office. He is the first <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> governor to be impeached. If convicted by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> would be succeeded by Secretary of State <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, a Democrat who is acting governor pending the impeachment trial's outcome.
</TEXT>
