<HEAD>Comatose Man Used As Human Guinea Pig Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMIENS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young man whose body was used for a medical experiment while he was in a deep coma died on Sunday, family members said. The revelation last Tuesday that an anesthesiologist had performed an experiment on <PERSON> Pacal </PERSON> <PERSON> Louette </PERSON>, 24, considered at the time clinically dead, touched off a scandal about the ethics of using human beings as guinea pigs. <PERSON> Louette </PERSON>, injured in an auto accident earlier this year, died Sunday morning at <LOCATION> Amiens </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, his father-in-law, <PERSON> Emile </PERSON> <PERSON> Collard </PERSON>, said. It was not immediately known whether there was a link between the death and the experiment in which Dr. <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Amiens </LOCATION> placed <PERSON> Louette </PERSON> on a sabotaged medical device. <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> was trying to see if the effects would match those of a similar case which has resulted in a trial of three doctors. Last Wednesday, Health Minister <PERSON> Michele </PERSON> <PERSON> Barzach </PERSON> suspended <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> from his duties as chief anesthesiologist at the hospital center. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> condemned such medical exercises, saying neither scientific progress nor the search for truth could justify them. <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> had told his superiors about the experiment, which he videotaped. It was the second time <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> said he had used a comatose human being for an experiment. In 1985, he experimented on a 20-year-old comatose man in a chronic vegetative state, setting off a scandal. That person also died, but no link was established between the experiment and the death. At the time, <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> called such patients `` almost perfect human models, who constitute intermediaries between animal and man.'' The latest experiment was made public in testimony Tuesday by Dr. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Lassner </PERSON>, a medical expert at a trial in the town of <LOCATION> Poitiers </LOCATION> where three doctors are charged in connection with the 1984 death of a 33-year-old woman. The woman, <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> <PERSON> Berneron </PERSON>, died after the removal of a tumor. She apparently had received nitrogen oxide instead of oxygen during resuscitation. A report showed that the tubes of the resuscitation system had been switched. <PERSON> Milhaud </PERSON> had informed <PERSON> Lassner </PERSON> of his experiment but has refused all comment since the court testimony.
