<HEAD>Book By Vermont Author Outlines Home Burial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINESBURG, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> borrowed a truck to take her husband's body to the crematory after he shot himself in 1981. In the early hours of the morning, she could think clearly enough only to know she did n't have the money to pay a funeral home. His ashes are buried in the garden behind their country home, the spot marked by a slab of granite on which she etched his name, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON>, with a pocket knife. She regrets only that she did n't share the intimate farewell with her husband's mother and the couple's children. Now <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> has written a book to help other people make their own funeral arrangements. She began writing it after her current husband, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>, and his three brothers buried their mother in a pine box atop a ridge. `` It's very easy to understand why people give it away to a funeral home, and indeed, if I had had the money, I would have given away a very special opportunity,'' <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said during a recent interview at her home. Her book, `` Caring for Your Own Dead,'' includes a directory of each state's laws on funeral arrangements, cremation and home burial, a glossary of terms and instructions on completing a death certificate. It also includes a listing of medical schools that accept body donations. `` I really tried to take the mystery out of body disposition,'' <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said. Many states allow funerals to be handled privately, but <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said there may be obstacles to obtaining needed information on short notice, including some funeral directors reluctant to offer prices over the telephone and local officials unaccustomed to the idea. She credits many in the funeral industry for their help during her nine months of researching the book. She found that anyone in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> can do a home burial as long as technical requirements involving the death certificate are met. If the burial is to be on private property it must be away from power lines and water and may be subject to local zoning restrictions. The town clerk keeps a map of private burial plots. According to <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, a cremation could cost as little as $ 130, including a permit. Transportation and a box would add to the cost. `` The professional services and cost of the casket are two of the major expenses,'' <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said. In 1987, the average cost of a funeral, including professional services and a casket, was $ 2,935, according to an industry newsletter, Funeral Service Insider. <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> took on her husband's funeral first from financial necessity. But then she realized that `` not only was it all right, it became clear to me that I needed to do it.'' One funeral director whom she had interviewed for the book called her after his 7-year-old son died. `` He did n't realize until afterwards how important it was for him to be involved personally,'' she said. Most states do not limit the family in caring for their dead, but some prohibit home burial and limit the scattering of ashes, her book says. About 80 percent of the 500 crematories <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> contacted across the country will accept a body from someone other than a funeral director. No state requires a body to be embalmed in every case, but many require it if a person died of a contagious disease, the book says. In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, a body may not be closed after an autopsy. In most of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, burial must be in an established cemetery. <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> has no state licensing requirements for funeral directors, so anyone may handle a funeral. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>'s book, there are limits on private funerals and home burial in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Other states where the family's involvement in funeral arrangements may be limited are <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, she says.
