<HEAD>Cigarette Suit Evidence Has A Common Thread: Lawyers Usually Cast
Shadows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 During the first month of a cigarette liability trial, anti-tobacco attorneys have introduced stacks of documents and presented 10 witnesses. Through much of the evidence runs a common thread: lawyers and more lawyers. Attorneys for the plaintiff argue that cigarette company attorneys kept a keen eye on smoking and health research, helped shape corporate policy and vetoed putting safer smokes on the market. One reason, according to the plaintiff's theory, is because the companies felt that if they acknowledged the dangers of smoking _ either through public statements or marketing of a less dangerous product _ they would be open to lawsuits over existing cigarettes. The trial of <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, makers of the brands that <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> smoked for 40 years before she died of lung cancer at the age of 58 in 1984, enters its second month Monday. Her husband, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON>, is pursuing a suit she filed before she died and is asking for unspecified damages. Attorneys for the tobacco companies say legal concerns did not dictate research. `` Lawyers are involved in decisions of industry all over the place,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, an attorney for the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, of firm <ORGANIZATION> Shook </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hardy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Bacon </LOCATION>, which represents <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION>. He said lawyers need to be familiar with research and scientific developments because of the rising tide of lawsuits against the cigarette-makers since the early 1950s and to advise clients on advertising and testimony before public bodies. The evidence so far has addressed three of the plaintiffs' allegations _ that the defendants knew how to make a safer cigarette but did n't; knew of potential health hazards from the 1920s through 1940s but did not act enough on the knowledge and failed to tell consumers; and sought to suppress or shape in their favor research on the hazards of smoking The jury has heard the testimony of former in-house and external researchers, top corporate executives and an expert on smoking and health. Testimony during most of last week was from <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullman </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, chairman emeritus and former president of <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edell </PERSON>, representing the <LOCATION> Cipollone </LOCATION> estate, asked <PERSON> Cullman </PERSON>, for example, if the company's general counsel `` advised'' him on cigarette smoking and health issues. `` He would n't advise,'' <PERSON> Cullman </PERSON> said. `` He would monitor them, I'd say.'' Several confidential documents introduced into evidence Thursday appear to indicate the role of lawyers. A letter dated April 29, 1974, from the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> to an official of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, describes a committee of manufacturers formed to study industry-funded research programs. The council itself was funded by tobacco companies. The <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> executive named the committee's chairman as <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>, the named partner in the Shook, <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> firm handling the current trial. A July 3, 1974, memo to committee members from another Shook, <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> attorney speaks of `` gaps in knowledge'' in the smoking-health field. Included is mention of a paper by tobacco council lawyer <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> with a section described as `` a summarization and slight updating of research recommendations.'' Before <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> assumed control of the manufacturers' research study committee, he corresponded with a tobacco council scientist, another memo showed. A Dec. 24, 1969, letter indicates the researcher, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Furst </PERSON>, had discussed with <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> the work of a British cancer researcher. Furst recommended to <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> that the British researcher, H.J. <PERSON> Eysenck </PERSON>, a psychologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Bethlem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Maudsley </LOCATION> hospitals in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, be given money for a pilot project. The letter said <PERSON> Eysenck </PERSON> had a theory that `` there may be a relationship between the appearance of cancer for some people and their emotional make up.'' Twelve years later, <PERSON> Eysenck </PERSON> wrote to <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> to ask for more research council funding, although it is unclear from the letter, also introduced last week, what the project involved.
