<HEAD>Tutu: Church Must Take Lead Role In Apartheid Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> and other religious leaders called Sunday for a sweeping campaign of defiance against new restrictions on opposition groups. Prominent clergy told their congregations that the church would become more active in opposing apartheid now that the government has banned political activity by 18 opposition groups. They called for a church-led campaign against the latest crackdown. `` We have no option but to engage in activities that now are prohibited,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Council of Churches. `` No matter what the consequences, we will continue to seek the unbanning of democratic organizations and the transfer of power from the white minority to all the people,'' <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON> told about 200 people at <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. The government on Wednesday banned the 18 black-led groups from political activity and placed restrictions on the activities of 18 senior black leaders. Church groups were n't included in the crackdown and theoretically still were free to engage in resistance campaigns, but most forms of peaceful protest still are banned under existing regulations. The outlawing of the country's leading anti-apartheid groups, most of them affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> coalition </ORGANIZATION>, is viewed as a clear sign that the government intends to maintain a hard line against all political opponents. Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Storey </PERSON>, a prominent white minister and anti-apartheid activist, compared the crackdown with the government's 1960 decision to outlaw the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANI