<HEAD>High Prices Lure Backyard Farmers As Sap Starts Flowing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High maple syrup prices after two abysmal sugaring seasons have prompted more people to tap more trees as the sap starts running this year, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s agriculture chief says. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> syrup sells for as much as $ 43 a gallon, nearly double the price before back-to-back bad seasons. But demand has not lagged, said Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. `` What's really kept it up there is packaging in ever smaller packages. We talk about the price per gallon but nobody ever buys a gallon of syrup anymore,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said in an interview last week. The 150,000 gallons of maple syrup sold annually in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, most of it in gift shops and country stores, comes in jugs as small as a pint or less, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. But not all of it comes from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. `` There's some new production coming out of the woodwork in <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'' that is sold bulk to packagers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` But we have the aura _ a geographic chauvinism'' favoring <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> maple syrup. State law ensures that `` if you call it <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> maple syrup, it has to be made in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> estimated there are 400 commercial maple syrup producers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and 1,000 `` backyard farm-type people.'' `` We will tap a lot more trees this year, as a result of high prices,'' he said. `` Sales of equipment and tubing indicate a lot more people are getting in this year.'' Sap runs when temperatures dip below freezing at night and rise to the 40s in the day _ conditions that began to occur in some places earlier this month. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> produced 100,000 gallons of syrup in its best year, 1984. But during the last two years, warm weather day and night predominated, and production was around 30 percent of normal. Technology is revolutionizing the sugaring industry, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. He estimated more than 80 percent of taps this year will feed into tubing that carries sap directly to evaporators and other processing equipment, rather than into buckets. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> says higher syrup prices staying around for awhile, regardless of how good this season is. `` If we go in with cupboard bare, no carryover syrup from last season, prices will be substantially higher than previous years, even with a bumper crop.'' A co-owner of the state's largest syrup producer, <PERSON> Bascom </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Acworth </LOCATION>, said she was puzzled that demand has remained stable despite the price. `` I do n't buy maple syrup. I ca n't explain it,'' <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Bascom </PERSON> said. `` We made less gallons at a higher price -LRB- last year -RRB- and we came out about the same.''
