<HEAD>NATO Summit Has Roots In Reykjavik</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 17th graf, NATO has, to correct style on plural of forum
to forums, sted fora; SUBS last graf, At their, to fix time to this
week, sted next week</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The seeds of this week's summit meeting at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s sprawling headquarters were planted nearly 16 months ago when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> faced <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> across a plain wooden table in a house in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> and seemed to forget <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s interests. It was October 12, 1986, and as dusk crept over the windows at <ORGANIZATION> Hofdi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION> and the whole world waited, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> got into a hot negotiation about the possibility of scrapping all their nuclear missiles. They failed. But when details of the talks came out, Western <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies who had depended on a no-surprise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense and arms control style for 39 years wondered if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had forgotten to take their needs into consideration. `` We do n't think it's a fair accusation,'' said a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration official. `` We've consulted with the allies assiduously before and after <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, but there's no denying the perception is there among Europeans that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> was willing to make drastic reductions in nuclear weapons, over their heads.'' `` The summit in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> will give them a bully pulpit to get their views across,'' said the official, one of several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> summit planners who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity. `` That's not to say we do n't want a summit; we think it's important to have this meeting at this juncture, for sound, alliance reasons,'' the official said `` It will let President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> show that despite some of the recent dents in his Teflon shield, he is an active and commanding presence. But on a scale of one to 100, the Europeans want it 60 or 70 and we want it 40 or 30.'' The Europeans' aim for the first <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit since 1982 is not just to remind <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> of their interests as he heads for another meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the spring. It is to talk `` through him'' to whoever replaces <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as president next January and to set the stage for what is likely to be several years of alliance-wide agonizing over the future of its internal relationships and its dealings with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The leaders will gather at the sprawling <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> on Wednesday and Thursday. The public will be barred from all but a brief opening and brief closing session and several hours have been devoted to meetings without large numbers of aides. At the end, the leaders will issue a declaration summarizing their goals and ideals for <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s future. There also is talk of issuing a separate statement on conventional weapons. <PERSON> Rozanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state, said Sunday that two summit issues would be: `` how do we stay strong so that we do n't make the world safe for conventional war or invite it'' and how to get the Soviets to reduce their now-stronger non-nuclear forces? The Europeans fear that with the possibility of a nuclear-free world, they may end up with no protection against the superior Soviet forces. <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON>, interviewed on <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Newsmaker Sunday,'' said, however, she believes the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance will always have `` a combination of conventional and nuclear deterrents. On an issue prompted partly by domestic budget pressure on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> said the president will take <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> a message on `` burden-sharing,'' <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> jargon for dividing up the manpower and financial load of maintaining Western defenses. She did not say what the message would be but said, `` They can do more. We can do more.'' Any private understandings at the meeting will be transmitted to lower-level groups that have been working for months to provide answers to some of the questions posed by a new climate of East-West relations ushered in since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s accession. The leaders are less likely to dwell on the nuts and bolts of defense and arms control problems facing the alliance in the short run. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has already committed itself to a U.S.-Soviet plan to reduce long-range nuclear weaponry by 50 percent. Granted, there is still some haggling within <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> on the pace and scope of negotiations on short-range nuclear forces, chemical weapons and conventional forces. But the leaders are not expected to spend much time on these details, leaving those tasks to other officials and other forums. Nor is <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> expected to get into a general discussion of problems the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is having with some of the allies over the continuation of American base rights. Talks with those countries _ <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> _ are being handled elsewhere. Beyond the internal problems, perhaps hovering over them, is the broadest issue of all: the relevancy of the Western alliance at a time when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is exhibiting signs of major reform and appears to be more forthcoming than ever in meeting <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> demands _ like one for a withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The alliance has stuck together for four decades out of fear of an expansionist and untrustworthy <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> dominated by its military leaders. After nearly three years of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and no sign in letup in the ferment in his country and among some of his allies, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders are wondering how their alliance should respond. At their summit this week, `` I think it's going to be both a moment of looking at the success that the alliance has had and getting down to the hard issues ahead _ the analysis of the current situation in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the opportunities it might present,'' one official said.
</TEXT>
