<HEAD>Residents, Business Owners Fight Change from Clarks Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. RIGSBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKS HILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been compared with the colonies' fight to overthrow King <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> It's the little guy against the establishment, the underdog fighting for a principle. And it's all about <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which changed the name of <LOCATION> Clarks </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>, after the veteran Republican senator from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, without asking local residents what they thought of the idea. `` I think we should change the Constitution from ` We the people' to ` You the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. They could tell us what we need and what to call everything down here,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Elswick </PERSON>, owner of <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bait </LOCATION> and Tackle in <LOCATION> Appling </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga </LOCATION>. Some cite an emotional attachment to the name taken from this nearby tiny town when the 70,000-acre <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> lake was first filled 44 years ago. Others say they've built a business reputation on the name, bringing national fishing tournaments and speedboat races and investing in souvenirs. Others are upset about the way the name of the lake on the <LOCATION> Georgia-South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> border was changed. Rep. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, introduced a bill suggesting the change on Dec. 3, two days before <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>'s 85th birthday. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a similar measure on Dec. 4, and by Dec. 23, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had signed it into law. <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> said he was approached by the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Clarks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill-Russell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> about changing the lake's name The eight-member authority was created in 1946 to `` assist, promote and cooperate'' in the development of the <PERSON> Clarks </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> lakes on the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McAllister </PERSON> said the board members, appointed by the governor, decided amongst themselves that naming the lake after <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON> would be a good idea because of all he's done to support the area. He said they did n't seek any public opinion because `` we were not making the final decision. We had no control over <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' But when <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., introduced the measure for the name change in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the authority's unanimous support was entered into the Congressional `` It was our impression that the local folks in the area were supportive of the change ...,'' said <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittinghill </PERSON>. A number of businessmen around the lake have posted petitions asking for a compromise _ change the name of the lake back to <PERSON> Clarks </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and leave the dam and the road across it named after <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, whose name is already on schools, federal buildings and streets around the state. The petitions are being distributed by a group called `` Keep <LOCATION> Our </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clarks </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>,'' led by <PERSON> Roy </P