<HEAD>McMartin Trial Into Tenth Month</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `The latest...', to CORRECT to last week,
sted this week. SUBS 19th graf, `The really...', to CLARIFY that
entire quotation is attributed to Gunson.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It has been 10 months since the trial began, seven months since the first witness appeared and an incredible five years since the <ORGANIZATION> McMartin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pre-School </ORGANIZATION> molestation case hit the courts. And there is no end in sight. Prosecutors say they will conclude their presentation by July, but the defense is n't saying how long it may take. `` Sometimes it irks me when people talk about how long it's been,'' says defense attorney Dean Gits, one of the players in this long-running drama on the 15th floor of the downtown Criminal Courts Building `` This has to be put into perspective. The case is absolutely unique,'' he said last week. `` We are dealing with allegations that cover four to five years. Murders do n't take that long; it's a split second. Rapes and robberies do n't take that long. `` How do you reconstruct a period of time that happened many, many years ago and covers four to five years? If people do n't understand that then they do n't understand why it's taking so long. Gits represents <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON>, 61, who is on trial along with her son, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON>, 29, charged with 100 child molestations at their now defunct family owned preschool in suburban <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. With time, the case has changed. Five teachers originally charged had their cases dismissed for lack of evidence. The prosecution, which once involved 41 children, now focuses on 13 youngsters who have grown from toddlers to pre-teen-agers. And the children's sometimes bizarre stories of satan worship, animal mutilation and trips to remote places have all but vanished. `` I sense that they have weeded out those -LRB- children -RRB- who went into fantasyland,'' says Gits. The latest child witness, a slender, 11-year-old boy, took the stand last week, telling jurors in 15 minutes what he remembered of his alleged molestation by <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON> and mentioning briefly that he once saw <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON> kill a horse. In a now familiar pattern, the cross-examination by Gits and <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, extended for days as the lawyers tried to elicit details which the prosecution never sought. Details of the horse incident, for example, were almost impossible to extract from the young witness who repeatedly answered, `` I do n't know.'' But the boy, nervous and embarrassed, told of being fondled and forced into oral copulation by <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON> and said he felt `` sick and dirty'' when he drew pictures of the incident for his mother. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> says he sees a pattern of fading memories. But Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Lael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, who has guided the case almost from its inception, says the child witnesses have improved with age. `` The children are more articulate. Their memories may not be as detailed as several years ago, but they're older, more articulate and less intimidated,'' she says. So far the jurors, who have sworn to stick with the trial no matter how long it lasts, have heard from only five of the children. Other prosecution witnesses called so far have included doctors, police officers and parents. `` The really important witnesses are the children themselves,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>'s co-counsel, Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunson </PERSON>. `` And the children have testified very well.'' The trial's duration has had a personal impact on all participants. The jurors, initially restless, have settled into a routine, taking copious notes. Many of them carry lunchboxes as if they are going to work. `` They've become part of the case and the commitment is coming through,'' says Gits. <PERSON> Gunson </PERSON> jogs and rides a bicycle to relieve tension. Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> found that they had enrolled in the same health club, and they often encounter each other working out in preparation for their courtroom battles. Gits shuns exercise, saying, `` When I want to relax I smoke a cigarette and drink a cup of coffee.'' The greatest strain is on the defendants. The gray-haired Mrs. <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON>, free on bail, sits and knits during recesses, chats with courtroom spectators or thumbs through a small Bible. `` She has her faith and believes very much that <PERSON> God </PERSON> has helped carry her through this,'' says Gits. Her son, who has been jailed without bail for nearly five years, was granted $ 3 million bail just before Christmas. In spite of pledges of property, he has been unable to raise the necessary $ 300,000 in cash to gain release. But <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> says his client is in `` pretty good spirits,'' sustained by the knowledge he will one day get to tell his side from the witness stand. Perhaps the most powerful figure in the courtroom is Superior Court Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pounders </PERSON>, who tries every day to move things along quickly. Last November, one year after he took over the <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON> case, <PERSON> Pounders </PERSON> marked the date by declaring, `` I do n't intend to see another anniversary date. I intend to conclude the case within the next year.''
