<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World merchandise trade grew more quickly last year than in 1986 and, barring economic upheavals, should expand at least as quickly this year, a report by a world trade group said Monday. The crash of world stock markets last October does not appear to `` have had an immediate adverse impact'' on global commerce, said the Secretariat of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. Early estimates show the volume of world merchandise trade rose by 4 percent last year compared to 3.5 percent in 1986, the world trade agency's analysts said. `` Barring a further major upheaval in financial markets or a serious recession in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it should grow at least as rapidly in 1988,'' they said. Last September, <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> had predicted only about 3.5 percent growth for 1987. The report expressed concern about trade imbalances among the world's largest economies. Also, Third World debt and protectionist pressures still burden the world economy, it said. But consumer and investor confidence has survived the stock crash better than analysts forecasted immediately after the crisis, the report said. `` The improvement in the outlook for trade in recent months means that, all other things being equal, the risk of a recession in 1988 is smaller,'' <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> chief economist <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackhurst </PERSON> said. The value of merchandise exports rose 15.5 percent in 1987 to a new record of $ 2.45 billion, partly reflecting the depreciation of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and higher prices for crude oil and other commodities, the report said. Manufactured goods led the expansion with a 5 percent rise in volume, up from 3.5 percent in 1986. Farm exports rebounded to an estimated 4 percent rise after a decline of 1 percent, the report said. Reduced petroleum trade helped push trade volume in mining products down 1 percent. Imports by industrialized market economies remained the strongest force in world trade expansion, though growth slowed to 5 percent from 8.5 percent in 1986, the report said. Another factor cited was fast growth in <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> economies such as <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. These countries have become significant buyers of manufactured goods on world markets as well as exporters, <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> said. Export growth in developing countries slowed to 6 percent from 9 percent in 1986, but remained more vigorous than in other parts of the world. The report noted improved trade performance by a group of 15 heavily indebted countries, including 10 in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. State-controlled economies like <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the Soviet bloc expanded their trade less than other countries, particularly because they squeezed imports to adjust to lower export revenues from fuels and debt service requirements, the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> includes about 100 member nations and was set up after World War II. It is both an agreement and a forum for removing trade barriers and ensuring the free movement of goods around the world. It is administered by a permanent commission by the same name in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
