<FIRST>r a AM-GourmetDelivery     02-28 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gourmet Delivery,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Mills Tests Market For Gourmet Delivery Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bow-tied drivers in refrigerated vans are rushing prime rib and triple-layer carrot cake to upscale homes here to test the water for home-delivered gourmet meals in an industry dominated by pizza. The creation of `` The Order Inn,'' an experimental division of food giant <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was spurred by some compelling demographics, industry analysts say. The secretive test targets affluent singles and professional couples. `` What we're seeing is the beginning of an escalating delivery war, not just with pizza but with all kinds of home-delivered food,'' said <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, vice president of marketing for Godfather's Pizza, an <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb.-based division of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` People are time-short and dollar-rich,'' said <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, whose company is shrinking sit-down areas in its new restaurants and mobilizing larger road forces. `` They do n't want to eat out. They're more than willing to pay to have it brought to their houses and I do n't see it ending.'' The explosion of convenience food in all its frozen and home-delivered variations can be traced to two late -'80s phenomena, said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnes </PERSON>, managing director of research for the brokerage firm of <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jaffray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Carnes </PERSON> said his company's research shows 65 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> homes now have microwave ovens and 55 percent of all married women work. Households typically are short on time for cooking and long on money to pay others to do it. But restaurants have shortcomings as an alternative to kitchen toil, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> and others note. Costs can be high and there's usually a wait Moreover, food industry analysts say that, in an age of VCRs, staying at home _ `` cocooning,'' as it's been dubbed _ is becoming an end in itself. Grocery stores around the country have scurried to meet the demand with wider offerings of prepared and semi-prepared dinners. The choices range from macaroni and cheese on the low end to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> broil and rattlesnake at the top. Even a drive to the grocery store can sometimes be too strenuous for the work-weary, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Flatow </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market research company <ORGANIZATION> BrainReserve </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The goal is delivering a nice dinner to them; the challenge is overcoming high cost and logistics. `` Domino's Pizza has done it. Now all you've got to do is get veal marsala there and you've got it,'' <PERSON> Flatow </PERSON> said. `` The need is there. Nobody has fulfilled it yet.'' A General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> spokesman would not discuss the Order Inn venture, citing competitive factors. Local analysts say it has been under way for roughly six months. Industry watchers describe it as a logical step for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION>, which also owns the Red Lobster, <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s and <LOCATION> Olive </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> restaurant chains. Based in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> suburb, the company also has takeout experience. It recently sold its chain of <PERSON> Leann </PERSON> <PERSON> Chin </PERSON>'s Chinese restaurants, which offered both sit-down and eat-at-home meals. Order Inn menus being dropped off at Twin Cities homes in recent months promise free delivery, usually in less than 20 minutes. Both lunches and dinners are available, seven days a week. The menu offers four selections in the appetizers and salad section, including chilled shrimp and popcorn chicken. Two sandwiches are available and five entrees, ranging from $ 5.75 for lasagna to $ 10.95 for prime rib. White-chocolate macadamia nut cheesecake highlights the three dessert choices. The menus include detailed instructions on reheating in a microwave or oven,. and a questionnaire asking what was ordered and how the food and service ranked. No verdict is in sight on the Order Inn, but experts say General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> seems to have the right idea. `` I do n't think there's any question there will be more to follow,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Carver </PERSON>, senior vice president of the <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> brokerage firm of <ORGANIZATION> Dain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bosworth </ORGANIZATION>. A chief obstacle to success is keeping costs under control. With pizza, for example, gasoline, drivers, insurance and other costs take a $ 3 to $ 4 slice out of a $ 10 pizza, Godfather's <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> says. An extra hurdle for Order Inn is the daily gamble on how many orders will be placed for each item. Leftovers must be disposed of at day's end, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulstad </PERSON> confirmed. Whatever the future of the experiment, industry watchers predict scratch cooking will become ever more a recreational, weekend pastime. And restaurants, they say, should beware. `` It's really a fight for share of stomach,'' <PERSON> Carver </PERSON> said.
