<HEAD>Volcker Ends Self-Imposed Silence _ But Who Is Listening?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Does anyone pay attention to a 6-foot-7 kibbitzer who used to be the second most powerful man in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>? <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> is beginning to find out. The former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> recently broke a self-imposed vow of silence to resume offering opinions on deficits, taxes and the health of the economy. He seemed to show a little of the old magical influence last Thursday when stock and bond prices sank soon after he called for a tax increase and predicted that interest rates would rise. But some skeptics said the markets' behavior had nothing to do with what <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> said. `` He's not even associated with the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> anymore,'' said <PERSON> Hildegarde </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagorski </PERSON>, a market strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` When you get a day like -LRB- Thursday -RRB-, everybody tries to say what killed the market and they drag out every news item that would have passed unnoticed,'' she said. So is <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> capable of moving the market? `` No. Not at all,'' Ms. <PERSON> Zagorski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> still has not settled down to a new job since his departure from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> last August, when he was succeeded by <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> is expected to announce his career decision within the next few weeks. Meanwhile, he is borrowing an office on Wall Street and heading a Washington-based commission on how to improve the quality of the nation's civil service. Speaking on the lecture circuit helps pay the bills and gives <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> a forum to express his views on the need to cut the federal budget deficit. The forum for his remarks Thursday was a luncheon meeting in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION>. The night before, <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> had spoken in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Day banquet of the <ORGANIZATION> Creve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> was chosen as a contrast to the 1987 speaker, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>. `` We certainly know it's difficult to upstage a <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>, so we said let's go back to something that's not comparable,'' said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Allovio </PERSON>, the club's vice president. According to those who believe in <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>'s continuing influence, his remarks in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> triggered a selloff in the bond market, which scared owners of stock-index futures, which in turn dragged down stock prices. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had been up as much as 33 points, ended up with a loss for the day of 22.38 points, most of it in the final hour of trading. `` I have deep respect for <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> and in my opinion there is not a single more influential economist in this country,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON>, executive vice president and chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Clayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZ