<HEAD>Auto Engineers Gather in Detroit Monday Through Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 5,000 automotive engineers will meet this week to talk about everything concerning the life of a vehicle, from computerized conception to disposal on the junk heap. The Society for Automotive Engineers 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and Exposition also will be attended by more than 700 industry suppliers, who will display their latest developments in automotive plastics and other materials, lubricants, design systems and maintenance. They'll occupty 167,000 square feet of exhibit space at <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s downtown Cobo Hall from Monday through Thursday. The convention's theme is `` Engineering for the'90s _ Imagination, Innovation.'' Among featured speakers will be <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudd </PERSON>, deputy chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> Special sessions include a panel's look at the growing problem of disposing of automotive plastics as their use expands internally, in the engine and passenger compartment, and externally, as more and more body parts are composed of stronger, reinforced plastic substances. The engineers also will discuss efforts to reduce release of ozone-depleting chloroflourocarbons, or CFCs, used in production. Automaking has been the main source of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> emissions since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ended <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use in aerosol sprays in the 1970s. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Vice Chairman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> will be honored Monday at a luncheon hosted by <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, which named him its Man of the Year for 1988 The trade magazine noted <PERSON> Poling </PERSON>'s stabilizing, corporate-wide strategy of cost-cutting and balanced production while focusing on quality and cooperation with workers, dealers and suppliers. The strategy has allowed <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> to run factories at profitable levels, introduce attractive innovations and eliminate most plant closures, the magazine reported in a cover story on <PERSON> Poling </PERSON>. As a result, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> outearned <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, the much larger industry leader, in 1986 and 1987 and is expected to remain the biggest money-maker in the industry in 1988, while <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> is still fighting to cut costs and balance a huge modernization and new products program. Described as the largest vehicle engineering conference, the gathering will include engineers from <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> as well as hundreds of suppliers including Allied Automotive, <ORGANIZATION> Borg-Warner </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION>.
