<HEAD>Irving Bank, Target of Hostile Takeover, Predicts Bitter Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, target of a $ 1.08 billion hostile takeover proposal by <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> that was sanctioned last week by government regulators, said Sunday it would brief shareholders on why they should reject the bid and predicted a bitterly fought battle for their votes. `` Irving plans to bring to the attention of its shareholders all the factors they should consider regarding the offer, as well as questioning exactly how <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> intends to meet the numerous conditions to which its offer is now subject,'' the bank said in a press statement. It was <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s first official reaction to the approval given last Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s hostile $ 60 a share bid in cash and securities. The takeover fight has attracted attention because hostile acquisitions are unusual in the normally staid banking world. Some analysts have said government approval portends hostile takeovers of other banks. Fed and state officials dismissed the unfriendly nature of the bid as irrelevant and said they saw no competitive threat to a merger of the two <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION>, which would create the nation's 12th largest banking company with assets of nearly $ 42 billion Nevertheless, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> imposed one important condition of approval by requiring <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> to sell additional stock to replenish the $ 264 million cash portion of the takeover. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said at least 60 percent of that amount must be raised before the transaction can be completed. Although <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> officials expressed confidence they could meet the condition, <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> called it significant hurdles because it will dilute the stock's value and must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> shareholders. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s offer depends on receipt of two-thirds of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s shares. The offer could encounter more difficulty because of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law that impedes hostile takeovers. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s approval `` clearly opens the way for a bitterly fought proxy battle.'' Proxies are written statements authorizing others to vote stock on the behalf of shareholders, a normal arrangement in publicly held companies. Management routinely solicits shareholder proxies but they are also used by others attempting to win control away from management. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s approval does not change the nature of the proposal, which continues to make no business sense and is not in the best long-term interest of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>,'' said the Irving statement. It said the bank `` is fully committed to continue opposing this grossly inadequate and highly conditional proposal, which the corporation's unanimous board is convinced is not in <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s best interests.''
